 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "108271eb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# KNN Shapley"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4be9ecb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This notebook shows how to calculate Shapley values for the K-Nearest Neighbours algorithm. By making use of the local structure of KNN, it is possible to compute an exact value in almost linear time, as opposed to exponential complexity of exact, model-agnostic Shapley.\n",
    "\n",
    "The main idea is to exploit the fact that adding or removing points beyond the k-ball doesn't influence the score. Because the algorithm then essentially only needs to do a\n",
    "search it runs in $\\mathcal{O}(N \\log N)$ time.\n",
    "\n",
    "By further using approximate nearest neighbours, it is possible to achieve $(\\epsilon,\\delta)$-approximations in sublinear time. However, this is not implemented in pyDVL yet.\n",
    "\n",
    "We refer to the original paper that pyDVL implements for details: *Jia, Ruoxi, David Dao, Boxin Wang, Frances Ann Hubis, Nezihe Merve Gurel, Bo Li, Ce Zhang, Costas Spanos, and Dawn Song. [Efficient Task-Specific Data Valuation for Nearest Neighbor Algorithms](https://doi.org/10.14778/3342263.3342637). Proceedings of the VLDB Endowment 12, no. 11 (1 July 2019): 1610â€“23.*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e379577",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setup\n",
    "We begin by importing the main libraries and setting some defaults.\n",
    "\n",
    "**If you are reading this in the documentation, some boilerplate is left out for your convenience.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "c3a76161",
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%load_ext autoreload"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "57174af3",
   "metadata": {
    "nbsphinx": "hidden"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%autoreload\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "import random\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import sklearn as sk\n",
    "from copy import deepcopy\n",
    "from pydvl.utils.plotting import plot_iris\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"figure.figsize\"] = (20, 8)\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"font.size\"] = 12\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"xtick.labelsize\"] = 12\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"ytick.labelsize\"] = 10\n",
    "random_state = 24\n",
    "random.seed(random_state)\n",
    "np.random.seed(random_state)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "75abb359",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The main entry point is the function [compute_shapley_values()](../pydvl/shapley.rst#pydvl.shapley.compute_shapley_values), which provides a facade to all Shapley methods. In order to use it we need the classes [Dataset](../pydvl/utils/dataset.rst#pydvl.utils.dataset.Dataset) and [Utility](../pydvl/utils/utility.rst#pydvl.utils.utility.Utility)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "31eee9a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from pydvl.utils import Dataset, Utility\n",
    "from pydvl.shapley import compute_shapley_values"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d60eb5aa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Building a Dataset and a Utility\n",
    "\n",
    "We use [the sklearn iris dataset](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/datasets/plot_iris_dataset.html) and wrap it into a [pydvl.utils.dataset.Dataset](../pydvl/utils/dataset.rst#pydvl.utils.dataset.Dataset) calling the factory [pydvl.utils.dataset.Dataset.from_sklearn()](../pydvl/utils/dataset.rst#pydvl.utils.dataset.Dataset.from_sklearn). This automatically creates a train/test split for us which will be used to compute the utility.\n",
    "\n",
    "We then create a model and instantiate a [Utility](../pydvl/utils/utility.rst#pydvl.utils.utility.Utility) using data and model. The model needs to implement the protocol [pydvl.utils.types.SupervisedModel](../pydvl/utils/types.rst#pydvl.utils.types.SupervisedModel), which is just the standard sklearn interface of `fit()`,`predict()` and `score()`. In constructing the `Utility` one can also choose a scoring function, but we pick the default which is just the model's `knn.score()`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "7eed1d8d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sklearn_dataset = sk.datasets.load_iris()\n",
    "data = Dataset.from_sklearn(sklearn_dataset)\n",
    "knn = sk.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)\n",
    "utility = Utility(knn, data)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "efead0d7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Computing values\n",
    "\n",
    "Calculating the Shapley values is straightforward. We just call [pydvl.shapley.compute_shapley_values()](../pydvl/shapley.rst#pydvl.shapley.compute_shapley_values) with the utility object we created above. The function returns a [pandas DataFrame](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.html) where the index corresponds to sample indices and the values are in column `data_value`. The DataFrame is sorted by ascending `data_value`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "58bb9b4e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "25db2986aef24b08ae9ccfccb2c0c6df",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "0it [00:00, ?it/s]"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "shapley_values = compute_shapley_values(utility, mode=\"knn\", progress=True)\n",
    "values = shapley_values.data_value.to_numpy()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e402a3f2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Inspecting the results\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us first look at the labels' distribution as a function of petal and sepal length:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "467f635a",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": [
     "remove-input"
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x576 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_iris(\n",
    "    data,\n",
    "    legend_title=\"flower type\",\n",
    "    legend_labels=list(sklearn_dataset.target_names),\n",
    "    suptitle=\"Labels distribution\",\n",
    "    colorbar_limits=None,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e5f276c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we now look at  the distribution of Shapley values for each class, we see that each has samples with both high and low scores. This is expected, because an accurate model uses information of all classes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "a2715c13",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x576 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x576 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x576 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "class_ids = np.unique(data.y_train)\n",
    "for class_id in class_ids:\n",
    "    class_idxs = np.array(\n",
    "        [i for i, label in enumerate(data.y_train) if label == class_id]\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    plot_iris(\n",
    "        data,\n",
    "        indices=class_idxs,\n",
    "        colors=values[class_idxs],\n",
    "        legend_title=\"shapley values\",\n",
    "        suptitle=f\"Shapley values - {sklearn_dataset.target_names[class_id]}\",\n",
    "    )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f78c7050",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Corrupting labels\n",
    "\n",
    "To test how informative values are, we can corrupt some training labels and see how their Shapley values change with respect to the non-corrupted points."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "0daee474",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "corrupted_dataset = deepcopy(data)\n",
    "num_corrupted = 10\n",
    "corrupted_dataset.y_train[:num_corrupted] = (\n",
    "    corrupted_dataset.y_train[:num_corrupted] + 1\n",
    ") % 3\n",
    "knn = sk.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)\n",
    "contaminated_shapley = compute_shapley_values(\n",
    "    Utility(knn, corrupted_dataset), mode=\"knn\"\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "97e26e59",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Taking the average corrupted value and comparing it to non-corrupted ones, we notice that on average anomalous points have a much lower score, i.e. they tend to be much less valuable to the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "f0cd5a95",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Mean shapley value of corrupted points: -0.008934091047241414\n",
      "Mean shapley value of regular points: 0.010925156715879228\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "corrupted_shapley_values = contaminated_shapley.data_value.iloc[:num_corrupted]\n",
    "correct_shapley_values = contaminated_shapley.data_value.iloc[num_corrupted:]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Mean shapley value of corrupted points:\", corrupted_shapley_values.mean())\n",
    "print(\"Mean shapley value of regular points:\", correct_shapley_values.mean())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bb48402b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This is confirmed if we plot the distribution of Shapley values and circle corrupt points in red. They all tend to have low Shapley scores, regardless of their position in space and assigned label:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "686ded22",
   "metadata": {
    "jupyter": {
     "source_hidden": true
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x576 with 4 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_iris(\n",
    "    data,\n",
    "    colors=contaminated_shapley.data_value,\n",
    "    highlight_indices=np.arange(num_corrupted),\n",
    "    legend_title=\"shapley values\",\n",
    "    suptitle=\"Distribution of Shapley values\",\n",
    "    colorbar_limits=(-0.025, 0.027),\n",
    ")\n"
   ]
  }
 ],
